 of a data collection that exposes the <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Collections.Specialized.INotifyCollectionChanged&gt;</ph> interface.","pos":[35642,35953],"source":"[!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_winclient](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-winclient-md.md)] provides the <xref:System.Collections.ObjectModel.ObservableCollection%601> class, which is a built-in implementation of a data collection that exposes the <xref:System.Collections.Specialized.INotifyCollectionChanged> interface."},{"content":"Note that to fully support transferring data values from source objects to targets, each object in your collection that supports bindable properties must also implement the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.ComponentModel.INotifyPropertyChanged&gt;</ph> interface.","pos":[35954,36189],"source":" Note that to fully support transferring data values from source objects to targets, each object in your collection that supports bindable properties must also implement the <xref:System.ComponentModel.INotifyPropertyChanged> interface."},{"content":"For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Binding Sources Overview<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/data/binding-sources-overview.md)</ept>.","pos":[36190,36308],"source":" For more information, see [Binding Sources Overview](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/data/binding-sources-overview.md)."},{"content":"Before implementing your own collection, consider using <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Collections.ObjectModel.ObservableCollection%601&gt;</ph> or one of the existing collection classes, such as <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Collections.Generic.List%601&gt;</ph>, <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Collections.ObjectModel.Collection%601&gt;</ph>, and <ph id=\"ph4\">&lt;xref:System.ComponentModel.BindingList%601&gt;</ph>, among many others.","pos":[36315,36651],"source":"Before implementing your own collection, consider using <xref:System.Collections.ObjectModel.ObservableCollection%601> or one of the existing collection classes, such as <xref:System.Collections.Generic.List%601>, <xref:System.Collections.ObjectModel.Collection%601>, and <xref:System.ComponentModel.BindingList%601>, among many others."},{"content":"If you have an advanced scenario and want to implement your own collection, consider using <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Collections.IList&gt;</ph>, which provides a non-generic collection of objects that can be individually accessed by index and thus the best performance.","pos":[36652,36900],"source":" If you have an advanced scenario and want to implement your own collection, consider using <xref:System.Collections.IList>, which provides a non-generic collection of objects that can be individually accessed by index and thus the best performance."},{"pos":[36945,36961],"content":"Collection Views","linkify":"Collection Views","nodes":[{"content":"Collection Views","pos":[0,16]}]},{"content":"Once your <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ItemsControl&gt;</ph> is bound to a data collection, you may want to sort, filter, or group the data.","pos":[36965,37098],"source":"Once your <xref:System.Windows.Controls.ItemsControl> is bound to a data collection, you may want to sort, filter, or group the data."},{"content":"To do that, you use collection views, which are classes that implement the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.ComponentModel.ICollectionView&gt;</ph> interface.","pos":[37099,37229],"source":" To do that, you use collection views, which are classes that implement the <xref:System.ComponentModel.ICollectionView> interface."},{"pos":[37243,37269],"content":"What Are Collection Views?","linkify":"What Are Collection Views?","nodes":[{"content":"What Are Collection Views?","pos":[0,26]}]},{"content":"A collection view is a layer on top of a binding source collection that allows you to navigate and display the source collection based on sort, filter, and group queries, without having to change the underlying source collection itself.","pos":[37273,37509]},{"content":"A collection view also maintains a pointer to the current item in the collection.","pos":[37510,37591]},{"content":"If the source collection implements the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Collections.Specialized.INotifyCollectionChanged&gt;</ph> interface, the changes raised by the <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Collections.Specialized.INotifyCollectionChanged.CollectionChanged&gt;</ph> event are propagated to the views.","pos":[37592,37847],"source":" If the source collection implements the <xref:System.Collections.Specialized.INotifyCollectionChanged> interface, the changes raised by the <xref:System.Collections.Specialized.INotifyCollectionChanged.CollectionChanged> event are propagated to the views."},{"content":"Because views do not change the underlying source collections, each source collection can have multiple views associated with it.","pos":[37854,37983]},{"content":"For example, you may have a collection of <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Task<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> objects.","pos":[37984,38041],"source":" For example, you may have a collection of *Task* objects."},{"content":"With the use of views, you can display that same data in different ways.","pos":[38042,38114]},{"content":"For example, on the left side of your page you may want to show tasks sorted by priority, and on the right side, grouped by area.","pos":[38115,38244]},{"pos":[38294,38314],"content":"How to Create a View","linkify":"How to Create a View","nodes":[{"content":"How to Create a View","pos":[0,20]}]},{"content":"One way to create and use a view is to instantiate the view object directly and then use it as the binding source.","pos":[38318,38432]},{"content":"For example, consider the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Data Binding Demo<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=163703)</ept> application shown in the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>What Is Data Binding?<ept id=\"p2\">](#what_is_data_binding)</ept> section.","pos":[38433,38606],"source":" For example, consider the [Data Binding Demo](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=163703) application shown in the [What Is Data Binding?](#what_is_data_binding) section."},{"content":"The application is implemented such that the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListBox&gt;</ph> binds to a view over the data collection instead of the data collection directly.","pos":[38607,38772],"source":" The application is implemented such that the <xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListBox> binds to a view over the data collection instead of the data collection directly."},{"content":"The following example is extracted from the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Data Binding Demo<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=163703)</ept> application.","pos":[38773,38896],"source":" The following example is extracted from the [Data Binding Demo](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=163703) application."},{"content":"The <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource&gt;</ph> class is the <ph id=\"ph2\">[!INCLUDE[TLA#tla_xaml](../../../../includes/tlasharptla-xaml-md.md)]</ph> proxy of a class that inherits from <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionView&gt;</ph>.","pos":[38897,39110],"source":" The <xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource> class is the [!INCLUDE[TLA#tla_xaml](../../../../includes/tlasharptla-xaml-md.md)] proxy of a class that inherits from <xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionView>."},{"content":"In this particular example, the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource.Source%2A&gt;</ph> of the view is bound to the <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>AuctionItems<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> collection (of type <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Collections.ObjectModel.ObservableCollection%601&gt;</ph>) of the current application object.","pos":[39111,39362],"source":" In this particular example, the <xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource.Source%2A> of the view is bound to the *AuctionItems* collection (of type <xref:System.Collections.ObjectModel.ObservableCollection%601>) of the current application object."},{"pos":[39846,39995],"content":"The resource <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>listingDataView<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> then serves as the binding source for elements in the application, such as the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListBox&gt;</ph>:","source":"The resource *listingDataView* then serves as the binding source for elements in the application, such as the <xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListBox>:"},{"pos":[40280,40445],"content":"To create another view for the same collection, you can create another <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource&gt;</ph> instance and give it a different <ph id=\"ph2\">`x:Key`</ph> name.","source":"To create another view for the same collection, you can create another <xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource> instance and give it a different `x:Key` name."},{"content":"The following table shows which view data types are created as the default collection view or by <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource&gt;</ph> based on the source collection type.","pos":[40452,40633],"source":"The following table shows which view data types are created as the default collection view or by <xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource> based on the source collection type."},{"content":"Source collection type","pos":[40640,40662]},{"content":"Collection view type","pos":[40663,40683]},{"content":"Notes","pos":[40684,40689]},{"content":"An internal type based on <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionView&gt;</ph>","pos":[40804,40871],"source":"An internal type based on <xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionView>"},{"content":"Cannot group items.","pos":[40872,40891]},{"content":"Fastest.","pos":[40974,40982]},{"pos":[41095,41115],"content":"Using a Default View","linkify":"Using a Default View","nodes":[{"content":"Using a Default View","pos":[0,20]}]},{"content":"Specifying a collection view as a binding source is one way to create and use a collection view.","pos":[41119,41215]},{"content":"WPF also creates a default collection view for every collection used as a binding source.","pos":[41216,41305]},{"content":"If you bind directly to a collection, WPF binds to its default view.","pos":[41306,41374]},{"content":"Note that this default view is shared by all bindings to the same collection, so a change made to a default view by one bound control or code (such as sorting or a change to the current item pointer, discussed later) is reflected in all other bindings to the same collection.","pos":[41375,41650]},{"content":"To get the default view, you use the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource.GetDefaultView%2A&gt;</ph> method.","pos":[41657,41767],"source":"To get the default view, you use the <xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource.GetDefaultView%2A> method."},{"content":"For an example, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Get the Default View of a Data Collection<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/data/how-to-get-the-default-view-of-a-data-collection.md)</ept>.","pos":[41768,41921],"source":" For an example, see [Get the Default View of a Data Collection](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/data/how-to-get-the-default-view-of-a-data-collection.md)."},{"pos":[41933,41973],"content":"Collection Views with ADO.NET DataTables","linkify":"Collection Views with ADO.NET DataTables","nodes":[{"content":"Collection Views with ADO.NET DataTables","pos":[0,40]}]},{"content":"To improve performance, collection views for ADO.NET <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Data.DataTable&gt;</ph> or <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Data.DataView&gt;</ph> objects delegate sorting and filtering to the <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Data.DataView&gt;</ph>.","pos":[41977,42164],"source":"To improve performance, collection views for ADO.NET <xref:System.Data.DataTable> or <xref:System.Data.DataView> objects delegate sorting and filtering to the <xref:System.Data.DataView>."},{"content":"This causes sorting and filtering to be shared across all collection views of the data source.","pos":[42165,42259]},{"content":"To enable each collection view to sort and filter independently, initialize each collection view with its own <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Data.DataView&gt;</ph> object.","pos":[42260,42405],"source":" To enable each collection view to sort and filter independently, initialize each collection view with its own <xref:System.Data.DataView> object."},{"pos":[42416,42423],"content":"Sorting","linkify":"Sorting","nodes":[{"content":"Sorting","pos":[0,7]}]},{"content":"As mentioned before, views can apply a sort order to a collection.","pos":[42427,42493]},{"content":"As it exists in the underlying collection, your data may or may not have a relevant, inherent order.","pos":[42494,42594]},{"content":"The view over the collection allows you to impose an order, or change the default order, based on comparison criteria that you supply.","pos":[42595,42729]},{"content":"Because it is a client-based view of the data, a common scenario is that the user might want to sort columns of tabular data per the value that the column corresponds to.","pos":[42730,42900]},{"content":"Using views, this user-driven sort can be applied, again without making any changes to the underlying collection or even having to requery for the collection content.","pos":[42901,43067]},{"content":"For an example, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Sort a GridView Column When a Header Is Clicked<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/controls/how-to-sort-a-gridview-column-when-a-header-is-clicked.md)</ept>.","pos":[43068,43237],"source":" For an example, see [Sort a GridView Column When a Header Is Clicked](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/controls/how-to-sort-a-gridview-column-when-a-header-is-clicked.md)."},{"pos":[43244,43514],"content":"The following example shows the sorting logic of the \"Sort by category and date\" <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.CheckBox&gt;</ph> of the application <ph id=\"ph2\">[!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_ui](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-ui-md.md)]</ph> in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>What Is Data Binding?<ept id=\"p1\">](#what_is_data_binding)</ept> section:","source":"The following example shows the sorting logic of the \"Sort by category and date\" <xref:System.Windows.Controls.CheckBox> of the application [!INCLUDE[TLA2#tla_ui](../../../../includes/tla2sharptla-ui-md.md)] in the [What Is Data Binding?](#what_is_data_binding) section:"},{"pos":[43796,43805],"content":"Filtering","linkify":"Filtering","nodes":[{"content":"Filtering","pos":[0,9]}]},{"content":"Views can also apply a filter to a collection.","pos":[43809,43855]},{"content":"This means that although an item might exist in the collection, this particular view is intended to show only a certain subset of the full collection.","pos":[43856,44006]},{"content":"You might filter on a condition in the data.","pos":[44007,44051]},{"content":"For instance, as is done by the application in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>What Is Data Binding?<ept id=\"p1\">](#what_is_data_binding)</ept> section, the \"Show only bargains\" <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.CheckBox&gt;</ph> contains logic to filter out items that cost $25 or more.","pos":[44052,44281],"source":" For instance, as is done by the application in the [What Is Data Binding?](#what_is_data_binding) section, the \"Show only bargains\" <xref:System.Windows.Controls.CheckBox> contains logic to filter out items that cost $25 or more."},{"content":"The following code is executed to set <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>ShowOnlyBargainsFilter<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> as the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource.Filter&gt;</ph> event handler when that <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.CheckBox&gt;</ph> is selected:","pos":[44282,44483],"source":" The following code is executed to set *ShowOnlyBargainsFilter* as the <xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource.Filter> event handler when that <xref:System.Windows.Controls.CheckBox> is selected:"},{"pos":[44765,44841],"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>ShowOnlyBargainsFilter<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> event handler has the following implementation:","source":"The *ShowOnlyBargainsFilter* event handler has the following implementation:"},{"content":"If you are using one of the <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionView&gt;</ph> classes directly instead of <ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource&gt;</ph>, you would use the <ph id=\"ph3\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionView.Filter%2A&gt;</ph> property to specify a callback.","pos":[45119,45367],"source":"If you are using one of the <xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionView> classes directly instead of <xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionViewSource>, you would use the <xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionView.Filter%2A> property to specify a callback."},{"content":"For an example, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Filter Data in a View<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/data/how-to-filter-data-in-a-view.md)</ept>.","pos":[45368,45481],"source":" For an example, see [Filter Data in a View](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/data/how-to-filter-data-in-a-view.md)."},{"pos":[45492,45500],"content":"Grouping","linkify":"Grouping","nodes":[{"content":"Grouping","pos":[0,8]}]},{"content":"Except for the internal class that views an <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Collections.IEnumerable&gt;</ph> collection, all collection views support the functionality of grouping, which allows the user to partition the collection in the collection view into logical groups.","pos":[45504,45751],"source":"Except for the internal class that views an <xref:System.Collections.IEnumerable> collection, all collection views support the functionality of grouping, which allows the user to partition the collection in the collection view into logical groups."},{"content":"The groups can be explicit, where the user supplies a list of groups, or implicit, where the groups are generated dynamically depending on the data.","pos":[45752,45900]},{"content":"The following example shows the logic of the \"Group by category\" <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.CheckBox&gt;</ph>:","pos":[45907,46012],"source":"The following example shows the logic of the \"Group by category\" <xref:System.Windows.Controls.CheckBox>:"},{"pos":[46290,46483],"content":"For another grouping example, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Group Items in a ListView That Implements a GridView<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/controls/how-to-group-items-in-a-listview-that-implements-a-gridview.md)</ept>.","source":"For another grouping example, see [Group Items in a ListView That Implements a GridView](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/controls/how-to-group-items-in-a-listview-that-implements-a-gridview.md)."},{"pos":[46494,46515],"content":"Current Item Pointers","linkify":"Current Item Pointers","nodes":[{"content":"Current Item Pointers","pos":[0,21]}]},{"content":"Views also support the notion of a current item.","pos":[46519,46567]},{"content":"You can navigate through the objects in a collection view.","pos":[46568,46626]},{"content":"As you navigate, you are moving an item pointer that allows you to retrieve the object that exists at that particular location in the collection.","pos":[46627,46772]},{"content":"For an example, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Navigate Through the Objects in a Data CollectionView<ept id=\"p1\">](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/data/how-to-navigate-through-the-objects-in-a-data-collectionview.md)</ept>.","pos":[46773,46950],"source":" For an example, see [Navigate Through the Objects in a Data CollectionView](../../../../docs/framework/wpf/data/how-to-navigate-through-the-objects-in-a-data-collectionview.md)."},{"content":"Because WPF binds to a collection only by using a view (either a view you specify, or the collection's default view), all bindings to collections have a